data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with proper MSTest collection assertions — each gives a much better failure message than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);                          // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));         // no built-in "all match" assertion; IsTrue is fine here
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);                         // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(                 // was: .Single() + Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
        users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Original | Better assertion | Why |
|----------|-----------------|-----|
| `IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(list)` | Says "expected non-empty, got empty" on failure |
| `IsTrue(list.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, list)` | Says "expected 3, got N" on failure |
| `.Single()` + null check | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | Asserts exactly one match and returns it |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` check has no specialized assertion in MSTest, so `Assert.IsTrue` is acceptable there. These APIs require **MSTest 3.8+**.
